      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Paul Bergevin was an American educator and author, co-developer of the Participation Training Institute, and Director of the Purdue-Indiana University Community Services in Adult Education.  He is the author or co-author of a number of books, papers and articles, including <emph render="italic">Design for Adult Education in the Church</emph> (1958), <emph render="italic">Adult Education in Sweden: An Introduction</emph> (1961), <emph render="italic">Adult Education Procedures  </emph> (1963), and <emph render="italic">Participation Training for Adult Education</emph> (1965).</p><p>In his <emph render="italic">A Philosophy For Adult Education</emph> (1967), Bergevin summarizes
twenty-two beliefs that are the basis for adult education, including "Adult education should be designed to help people to grow up, mature" and "Adults need to live together in community in order to grow and mature, and they need to learn how to do this."  The reading list at the end includes Aristotle, Thomas Jefferson, Thomas Hobbes, and Alfred North
Whitehead.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Paul Bergevin Papers</emph> consist of material relating to Bergevin's teaching and writing.  The collection has not been processed.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
